     Difficulty can arise in the development of a neural network when implementing backward propagation; in the past the most common issue that arose was that the optimization problem and the methodological approach to solve said optimization problem had to be hardcoded into the neural network code architecture. There exist no alternative to hardcoded implementations, and thus with this need to hardcoding one implementation - limited the depth that a neural networks could take, and the generality that a neural network algorithm could manifest so to be able to solve large data-driven problems, such as in Natural Language Processors (NLP) and advance image recognition or image manipulation software. To computate the partial derivatives needed to update each of the weight matrices and bais vectors, one had to implement an elaborate coding architecture that was hardcoded into the neural network code architecture, of which computated the desired partial derivatives that optimized the loss function optimization problem, but also updated the weight matrices and bais vectors.
     We hope that the difficulty of this approach has become apparent to the reader; the difficulty is that one needs not only to know the exact formulation of the partial derivatives in their analytic forms, but also know how to code said anayltic forms into the neural network's code architecture and have this implementation handle vectorized operations for efficient execution; e.g. as CPU can handle data in vector form more efficiently, implementing vectorized operations in the form of linear algebra matrix operations, significantly improves the computational efficiency of an algorithm. Though with the advent of forward automatic differentiation (FAD) [0] and reverved automatic differentiation (RAD) [1] the need for explicit hard-coding of the scheme to computate partial derivative become an antiquated practice; as if one can implement an RAD scheme, one can automate the computation process for attaining partial derivatives for the background propagation phase of training [1,2]. And unlike the traditional schemes of Numerical differentiation and Manual differentiation which approximates a complete or partial derivative; FAD and RAD schema both computate the exact complete or partial derivative avoiding the complication caused by trunction Error and roundoff Error, which are byproducts to the representation and computational limitations of Double-precision floating-point format (float64) and Extended-Double-precision floating-point format (float80) in the accepted standard IEEE-754 for Standard for Floating-Point Arithmetic [3,4,5,6]. The limitations of Standard for Floating-Point Arithmetic in the most commonly implemented float64 framework, results in serious limitations and contraints to the applicability to implement Numerical differentiation in algorithmic applications (e.g. use of Numerical differentiation) or algorithm development (e.g. implementation of Numerical differentiation in an algorithms' code architecture); but FAD and RAD hold no such Floating-Point Arithmetic limitations and it implementation lead to fluent automation, and it is for this reason why automatic differentiation schema have surplanted hard-coded derivative approximation schema in the world of machine learning and Artificial Intelligence.
     An open-source Python package named, PyTorch, developed by Meta AI research, seemingly popularized and proliferated the use of reversed automatic differentiation (RAD) in machine learning and AI development; Pytorch greatly simplified the process to implement backward propagation, which held back deep learning models of the past; instead of coding very complicated algebraic formed equations - attained through manual differentiation and executed with IEEE-754; one was able to rely on PyTorch Autograd Engine [7,8,9] to evaluate exact partial derivatives to each backward propagation process and pass it on to the respective optimization step. A more simplified RAD schema for Python was developed by an AI researcher, Andrej Karpathy, Micrograd; a self-contained open-source machine learning package. Being a self-contained package like PyTorch, Micrograd contains all the necessary functionality needed to implement any machine learning algorithm and deep learning model. The purpose of this project is to demonstrate the functionality of Micrograd, and it utility as a self-contained open-source package to develop machine learning and deep learning models for the purposes research and low-intensity application. For the purposes of this project, we did not simply import Micrograd and implement its packaged functions, instead we used a slightly modified version of the source-code to apply it to a series of applications; Micrograd's GitHub's page can be found here [10].

class Value:
    """ stores a single scalar value and its gradient """ # Credit to Andrej Karpathy 
                                                          # for the source code to Micrograd.Value

    def __init__(self, data,_children=(),_op=''):
        self.data=data;
        self.grad=0;
        # internal variables used for autograd graph construction
        self._backward=lambda: None;
        self._prev=set(_children);
        # the op that produced this node, for graphviz / debugging / etc
        self._op=_op; 
    def __add__(self, other):
        other=other if isinstance(other, Value) else Value(other);
        out=Value(self.data+other.data,(self,other),'+');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=out.grad
            other.grad+=out.grad
        out._backward=_backward
        return out;
    def __mul__(self,other):
        other=other if isinstance(other,Value) else Value(other);
        out=Value(self.data*other.data,(self,other),'*');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=other.data*out.grad;
            other.grad+=self.data*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def __pow__(self,other):
        assert isinstance(other,(int,float)),"only supporting int/float powers for now";
        out=Value(self.data**other,(self,),f'**{other}');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(other*self.data**(other-1))*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def log(self):
        x=self.data;
        out=Value(np.log(x),(self,),'Log');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(1*self.data**-1)*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def cos(self):
        x=self.data;
        out=Value(np.cos(x),(self,),'Cos');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(-1*np.sin(self.data))*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def sin(self):
        x=self.data;
        out=Value(np.sin(x),(self,),'Sin');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(-1*np.cos(self.data))*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def tan(self):
        x=self.data;
        out=Value(np.tan(x),(self,),'Tan');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=((1/np.cos(x))**2)*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def sqrt(self):
        x=self.data;
        out=Value(np.sqrt(self.data),(self,),'sqrt');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(1/(2*np.sqrt(self.data)))*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def relu(self):
        out = Value(0 if self.data < 0 else self.data,(self,),'ReLU');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(out.data > 0)*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def tanh(self):
        x=self.data;
        #t=(math.exp(2*x)-1)/(math.exp(2*x)+1);
        t=np.tanh(x);
        out=Value(t,(self,),'tanh');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(1-t**2)*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def sigmoid(self):
        x=self.data;
        t=(1/(1+np.exp(x)));
        out=Value(t,(self,),'Sigmoid');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(np.exp(x)/((np.exp(x)+1)**2))*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def softplus(self):
        x=self.data;
        out=Value(np.log(1+np.exp(self.data)),(self,),'softplus');
        def _backward():
            self.grad+=(1/(1+np.exp(-1*self.data)))*out.grad;
        out._backward=_backward;
        return out;
    def backward(self):
        # topological order all of the children in the graph
        topo=[];
        visited=set();
        def build_topo(v):
            if v not in visited:
                visited.add(v);
                for child in v._prev:
                    build_topo(child);
                topo.append(v);
        build_topo(self);
        # go one variable at a time and apply the chain rule to get its gradient
        self.grad=1;
        for v in reversed(topo):
            v._backward();
        pass
    def __neg__(self): # -self
        return self*-1;
    def __radd__(self,other): # other + self
        return self+other;
    def __sub__(self,other): # self - other
        return self+(-other);
    def __rsub__(self,other): # other - self
        return other+(-self);
    def __rmul__(self,other): # other * self
        return self*other;
    def __truediv__(self,other): # self / other
        return self*other**-1;
    def __rtruediv__(self, other): # other / self
        return other*self**-1;
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Value(data={self.data}, grad={self.grad})";

Lets get a little pathological, and select a pathological function to contruct next; it would be a perfect example to demonstrate reverved automatic differentiation (RAF), and compared its results to a manual differentiation - where we attained the analytic form of $f'(x)$. We selected the following pathological equation from a Real Analysis textbook, A First Course in Real Analysis, second edition, by M.H Protter and C.B. Morrey [14], its interesting behavior as a function, and the complexity of its first derivative made this pathological function the perfect demonstration function. But first let's derivative the analytic form of $f(x)$'s first derivative, $f'(x)$.


$$f(x)=\sqrt{\frac{3(x+2)(x^{2}+4)}{2(x^{2}+2x+4)}} \; \;\text{for interval} \; -2 \leq x \leq 5.$$


Manual differentiation by hand:


$$\frac{df}{dx}=\frac{d}{dx} \sqrt{\frac{3(x+2)(x^{2}+4)}{2(x^{2}+2x+4)}}=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \frac{d}{dx} \bigg[ \sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}} \: \bigg]$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \bigg( \frac{d}{dx}\big[ \sqrt{x^{2}+4} \: \big] \cdot \sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}} + \sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \frac{d}{dx} \bigg[ \sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}} \: \bigg] \bigg)$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \bigg( \frac{1}{2} \cdot \big( x^{2}+4 \big)^{-\frac{1}{2}} \cdot \frac{d}{dx} \big[ x^{2}+4 \big] \cdot \sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}} + \sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot \bigg( \frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4} \bigg)^{-\frac{1}{2}} \cdot \frac{d}{dx} \bigg[ \frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4} \: \bigg] \bigg)$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \Bigg( \frac{\big( \frac{d}{dx}\big[x^{2}\big]+\frac{d}{dx} \big[4\big]\big)\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}}{2\sqrt{x^{2}+4}} + \frac{\sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \frac{\frac{d}{dx}\big[x+2 \big] \cdot \big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)-(x+2) \cdot \frac{d}{dx}\big[ x^{2}+2x+4 \big]}{\big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)^{2}} }{2\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}} \Bigg)$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \Bigg( \frac{ 2x\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}}{2\sqrt{x^{2}+4}} + \frac{\sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \bigg( \frac{d}{dx}\big[x+2 \big] \cdot \big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)-\big(x+2\big) \cdot \frac{d}{dx}\big[ x^{2}+2x+4 \big] \bigg) }{2\big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)^{2}\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}} \Bigg)$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \Bigg( \frac{ 2x\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}}{2\sqrt{x^{2}+4}} + \frac{\sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \bigg( \big( \frac{d}{dx}\big[ x \big] + \frac{d}{dx} \big[ 2 \big] \big) \cdot \big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)-\big(x+2\big) \cdot \big( \frac{d}{dx}\big[ x^{2} \big] + \frac{d}{dx} \big[2x\big] + \frac{d}{dx} \big[ 4 \big] \big) \bigg)}{2\big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)^{2}\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}} \Bigg)$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \Bigg( \frac{ x\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}}{\sqrt{x^{2}+4}} + \frac{\sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \bigg( \big( 1+0\big) \cdot \big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)-\big(x+2\big) \cdot \big( 2x + 2 + 0 \big) \bigg)}{2\big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)^{2}\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}} \Bigg)$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \Bigg( \frac{ x\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}}{\sqrt{x^{2}+4}} + \frac{\sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \bigg( \big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)-\big(x+2\big) \cdot \big( 2x + 2 \big) \bigg)}{2\big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)^{2}\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}} \Bigg)$$

$$=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \cdot \Bigg( \frac{ x\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}}{\sqrt{x^{2}+4}} + \frac{\sqrt{x^{2}+4} \cdot \bigg( x^{2}-\big( x+2 \big)\big( 2x+2 \big)+2x+4 \bigg)}{2\big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)^{2}\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}} \Bigg)$$

$$=\frac{\sqrt{3}x^{2} \cdot \big( x^{2}+4x+12\big)}{2^{3/2}\sqrt{x^{2}+2x+4}\big( x^{2}+2x+4 \big)^{2}\sqrt{\frac{x+2}{x^{2}+2x+4}}}. \: \square$$


Though $f(x)$ is a pathological function, its first derivative is rather tamed compared to other pathological functions. Nevertheless, the high computational expense of manual differentiation should have become apparent from this example; this approach requires both a comprehension of differentiation rules and a mental facility to perform lengthy computation in one's head; simply this approach is not trivial and prone to human-error. This issue for attaining analytic form solutions to partial derivatives required in backward propagation to updates each of the respective weight matices and bais vectors, it should become apparent how acquiring an approach that could automate this computational process would allow the development of far more complicated neural networks and deep learning models. Before the advent of automatic differentiation, one had to manually attain the close form solutions to each partial derivative, it was a lengthy and complicated process.
     We computated the RAD and manual differentiation of $f(x)$, so that we could compare the accuracies of these two derivative schema, and so to demonstrate the process of automatic differentiation. After performing the computation and calculating a L-2 Norm Error, the difference between the result of automatic differentiation and the exact solution was $8.688869536365456e-16$, which is slightly greater then machine epsilon, $epsilon=2.220446049250313e-16$, which is the smallest floating-point representation on compliant Float64, e.g., Float64 is IEEE 754 double-precision binary floating-point [15].

# Reverse Automatic Differentiation
x=Value(np.linspace(-1.9999,-1,10));
y=((3*(x+2)*(x**2+4))/(2*(x**2+(2*x)+4))).sqrt();
y.backward();
# Exact manual derivative of the pathological function: f(x)
temp1=Value(3.0).sqrt(); temp2=Value(2)**(3/2); temp3=(x**2+4).sqrt(); temp4=((x+2)/(x**2+2*x+4)).sqrt();
Exact_Der=(temp1*(x**2)*(x**2+4*x+12))/(temp2*temp3*((x**2+2*x+4)**2)*temp4);
# Finite Difference Method - Numerical Differentiation
h=1.4901161193847656e-8;
Num_diff=((((3*((x+h)+2)*((x+h)**2+4))/(2*((x+h)**2+(2*(x+h))+4))).sqrt())-(((3*(x+2)*(x**2+4))/(2*(x**2+(2*x)+4))).sqrt()))/h;
print(" ")

For a visual representation and a further demonstration of the limits of Float64, we increased the $X$ interval partitions from ten to hundred-thousand, which significantly increased the computational cost; the result was the exact solution attained from the manual differentiation started to gain noise due round-off error which is caused when IEEE-754 runs out of digits to represent the numeric values, and must round the last digit values to the second last digit value. This adding of noise to the numeric value will acculumate over the many floating-point operations and will result in a perturbed result. Hence the slight perturbment of the exact derivative when implemented as a manually inputed formula; and furthermore, as Float64 can only represent a decimal numeric value to 16th digit, when IEEE-754 rounds out of digits during subtraction, it results in round-off error. The round-off error is far worst in the finite difference method [16], as one can see from the following results below: the L-2 norm Error between RAD/Manual Differentiation and Numerical Differentiation was $0.0037743527515596573$, which is eleven times larger then the L-2 norm Error between RAD and Manual Differentiation; a far worst result.

     Glancing at the graph above might give the impression that each differentiation schema are equivalently computationally stable and well-conditioned methods; though as displayed in L-2 norm error values, numerical differentiation is by far the worst method. Its issues lie entirely in the limitations with Float64, indeed the finite difference scheme is the definition of differentiation in calculus, but the underlynning concept of a infinitesimal value, such as $h$, is a impossible concept to implement in finite representation, without trunction or round-off; as a result the only feasible way to implement a finite difference scheme is to accept some degree of error in the final solution, and to properly measure an half way point to the current machine epsilon to choice a appropraite $h$ value. Converging to the point, this slight ill-conditionness of Numerical differentiation limits the application of such a numerical difference scheme to smaller neural networks, as the round-off error would be negligible at that size.
     Borrowing the Graphviz code from Andrej Karpathy YouTube video, The spelled-out intro to neural networks and backpropagation: building microghrad [17],


    # Url: https://graphviz.org/
    from graphviz import Digraph

    def trace(root):
        # Builds a set of all nodes and edges in a graph
        nodes,edges=set(),set()
        def build(v):
            if v not in nodes:
                nodes.add(v);
                for child in v._prev:
                    edges.add((child,v));
                    build(child);
        build(root);
        return nodes,edges;

    def draw_dot(root):
        dot=Digraph(format='svg',graph_attr={'rankdir': 'LR'}); # LR = left to right

        nodes,edges=trace(root)
        for n in nodes:
            uid=str(id(n));
            # for any values in the graph, create a rectangular ('record') node for it
            dot.node(name=uid,label="{data %.4f | grad %.4f}" % (n.data, n.grad),shape='record');
            if n._op:
                # if this value is a result of some operation, create an op node for it
                dot.node(name=uid+n._op,label=n._op);
                # and connect this node to it
                dot.edge(uid+n._op,uid);

        for n1,n2 in edges:
            # connect n1 to the op nodes of n2
            dot.edge(str(id(n1)),str(id(n2))+n2._op);

        return dot;


we were able to create two Digraphs that depicted the decomposition of differentials maps, one for AD and one for numerical differentiation. Firstly we choice $f(x)$ from the previous demonstrate to create the decomposition of differentials maps for both schema:

$$f(x)=\sqrt{\frac{3(x+2)(x^{2}+4)}{2(x^{2}+2x+4)}}.$$

Chose X=Value(1.75) for the x-value, and h=1.4901161193847656e-8 as the h-value. Now lets present the decomposition of differentials map for automatic differentiation, then present the decomposition of differentials map for numerical differentiation.



AD had to computate 18 partial derivatives to attain that $f^{'}(1.75) = 0.23420$, which is the exact derivative of $f^{'}(x)$ at $x=1.75$. In essence automatic differentiation is a decomposition method that decomposes a function to it element operations, then contructs the partial derivatives that exists in the differential segments between operations.
     Numerical differentiation is based on the finite difference schema which measures the in infinitesimal change in the value of $y$ from one x-value $x_{0}$ to another x-value $x_{1}$, and then normalizes the change over a infinitesimal $h$ which is the difference between $x_{0}$ and $x_{1}$, e.g., $h=x_{1}-x_{0}$.

$$\frac{df}{dx}=\frac{f(x_{1})-f(x_{0})}{x_{1}-x_{0}} \to \frac{df}{dx}=\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x_{0}+h)-f(x_{0})}{x_{0}+h-x_{0}} \to \frac{df}{dx}=\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x_{0}+h)-f(x_{0})}{h}$$

In essence the finite difference schema is a more sophicated slope formulation, which can accurate measure the slope of a function at any given x-value. Though because of the limitation of Float64, this schema is an ill-condition schema.



Numerical differentiation approximated that $f^{'}(1.75) \approx 0.3093$, though the exact derivative is $f^{'}(1.75) = 0.23420$, which mean numerical differentiation had an error of $0.0751$; which is quite a large error for a numerical algorithm. In mathematics an ideal accuracy for an mathematical algorithm would be machine epsilon $\epsilon$, but of course this is not always achievable due to feasibility, algorithmic limitations or computational limitations, so a lower standard is that a mathematical algorithm achieve an arruracy around $10^{-8}$, which is half the limitation of Float64. From this we can conclude that numerical differentiation is quite well ill-suited a mathematical algorithm for facilitating backward propagation, and instead more suitable algorithmic schema, such as, automatic differentiation and manual differentiation should be chosen to implement facilitate the backpropagation process.

     For larger neural networks automatic differentiation (AD) and manual differentiation schema are the most appropriate, as both of these schema are computationally stable and well-conditioned algorithms, and both provide a similar degree of accuracy. Though for deep learning models, it would be preferable to utilize an AD to computate the partial derivatives needed for backward propagation. A succinct and compendious explanation is that as layers are added to a standard neural network, said standard neural network slowly becomes a deep learning model, and thus the efforts required to derive and computate analytic form solutions to the partial derivatives speedily become a computationally expensive task, and furthermore, depending on the complexity of the loss function there might not exist a close form solution [18,19] to a some or all of the partial derivatives that are needed for backward propagation. In the case that a loss function's partial derivatives does not possess close form solutions, the only amendable approach would be to utilize numerical schema to approximate an analytic solution to each of the aforementioned partial derivatives, so to faliciate backward propagation. As we have shown numerical differentiation is an ill-suited algorithm for this task, though the algorithm could be utilized in certain implementations, it is not an ideal approach to resolving said issue; instead, a AD implementation is the solution to said issue, as it can attain the exact solution instead of an approximation and it can automate the backward propagation phase of training. In the case that the loss function's partial derivatives do possess close form solutions, then one would have to be derived the close form solutions by hand, then hardcode each close form solution into the neural networks code architecture, so that it may be executed during each training iteration.
     Nonetheless it is difficult to illustrate in words the complexity of implementing a manual differentiation approach to backward propagation, and so to better illustrate said complexity, we will borrow from Logistic Regression via FFNN (Feedforward Neural Network) [20], in said project, the author's objective was to implement a neural network logistic regression in Python utilizing numpy and scipy.special; the implementation utilized a manual differentiation approach to backward propagation, and so, it will service as a perfect example. In the following snippet of code contains the backward propagation function from [20], this snippet perfectly illustrates how one hardcodes the close form solutions of the partial derivative into the neural network code architecure.


    def backward_propagation(self,inputs,targets):
        m=inputs.shape[1];

        dZ_2=self.finaloutputs-targets;
        dW_2=(1/m)*np.dot(dZ_2,self.hiddenoutputs.T);
        db_2=(1/m)*(np.sum(dZ_2,axis=1,keepdims=True));
        dZ_1=np.dot(self.who.T,dZ_2)*(1-self.hiddenoutputs**2);
        dW_1=(1/m)*(np.dot(dZ_1,inputs.T));
        db_1=(1/m)*(np.sum(dZ_1,axis=1,keepdims=True));

        self.dW1=dW_1; self.db1=db_1; self.dW2=dW_2; self.db2=db_2;

        pass


Peeling back, but how did the authors derive the close form solutions of the loss function's partial derivatives? And what was the loss function? A logistic regression is useful for estimating probabilities of binary outcomes, or classifying binary outcomes; in the case of [20] the algorithm was a logistic regression classifier via feedforward neural network (FFNN), that was meant to classify credit card applicants for approval or decline for a credit card, from simulated credit card applicant dataset. In either case of likelihood estimate, or classification the loss function for a logistic regression is,


$$loss \: function=\frac{1}{m} \sum_{i}^{m} y_{i} \ln(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))+(1-y_{i})\ln(1-(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))) \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \text{(Eq. 1)}$$,

where $\sigma(W^{T}x+b=Final \: outputs)$, and where $W$ is the weight matrix between the hidden layer and output layer and $b$ is the subsequent bias vector and $\sigma()$ is the activation function. Simply a logistic regression is an optimization problem to find the probability value (e.g. critical point), $p$, that maximizes the Bernoulli Maximum Likelihood Estimate (MLE) function (Eq. 2) and minimizes the loss function (Eq. 3):


$$MLE= \text{arg} \max_{W \in \R} y_{i} \ln(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))+(1-y_{i})\ln(1-(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))) \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \text{(Eq. 2)}$$,

$$loss \: function= \text{arg} \min_{W \in \R} y_{i} \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i}^{m} y_{i} \ln(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))+(1-y_{1})\ln(1-(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))) \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \text{(Eq. 3)}$$.

To attain the gradients (e.g. partial derivatives) that maximize the Bernoulli MLE, we take the first-order partial derivative of (Eq. 2),


$$\frac{\partial MLE}{\partial W_{i}}=\frac{\partial MLE}{\partial W_{i}} \bigg( y \ln(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))+(1-y)\ln(1-(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))) \bigg)$$

$$=\frac{\partial MLE}{\partial W_{i}} y \ln(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))+\frac{\partial MLE}{\partial W_{i}}(1-y)\ln(1-(\sigma(W^{T}x+b))) \bigg)$$

$$=\bigg( \frac{y}{\sigma(W^{T}x+b)} - \frac{1-y}{1-\sigma(W^{T}x+b)} \bigg) \frac{\partial}{\partial W_{i}} \sigma(W^{T}x+b)$$

$$=\bigg( \frac{y}{\sigma(W^{T}x+b)} - \frac{1-y}{1-\sigma(W^{T}x+b)} \bigg) \sigma(W^{T}x+b)\big[1-\sigma(W^{T}x+b)\big]x_{i}$$

$$=\Bigg( \frac{y-\sigma(W^{T}x+b)}{\sigma(W^{T}x+b)\big[1-\sigma(W^{T}x+b)\big]} \Bigg) \sigma(W^{T}x+b)\big[1-\sigma(W^{T}x+b)\big]x_{i}$$

$$=\big[ y - \sigma(W^{T}x+b) \big]x_{i}. \; \square$$


After completing manual differentiation and algebraic manipulation we attained the simplified formula (Eq. 4),


$$\frac{\partial MLE}{\partial W_{i}}=\big[ y - \sigma(W^{T}x+b) \big]x_{i}\; \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \text{(Eq. 4)},$$


with this formulation we can attain each of the gradients (e.g. partial derivatives) needed to update the weight matrices and bais vectors.
     A neural network logistic regression contains three layers, one input layer, one hidden layer and one output layer, and hence, two weight matrices and two bais vectors. The first weight matrix is denoted Wih, as it is the weight matrix between the input layer and hidden layer; the second weight matrix is denoted Who as it is between the hidden layer and output layer. Subsequently, b1 represents the bias vector corresponding to Wih, while b2 is the bias vector to Wih. To devise the backward propagation phase, we need to derive the specific analytic forms to the gradients needed to update the weight matrices and bias vectors, to do so, we will derive the following formulations here,


$$\frac{\partial MLE}{\partial W_{i}}=\big[ y - \sigma(W^{T}x+b) \big]x_{i}$$

$$\to \frac{\partial MLE}{\partial Who_{i}}= \big[ final \: output - target \big] \cdot hidden \: output \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \text{(Eq. 5),}$$

$$\to \frac{\partial MLE}{\partial Who_{i}}= \bigg( Who^{T} \cdot \big[ final \: output - target \big] - Who^{T} \cdot \big[ final \: output - target \big] \cdot (hidden \: output)^{2} \bigg) * inputs \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \; \text{(Eq. 6).}$$


To attain the second gradient, $\frac{\partial MLE}{\partial Who_{i}}$, that correspondence to the hidden-output layer weight matrix, $Who$, we need to reformulate (Eq. 4)into what is found in Figure 4., as denoted as dw_2. To begin we need to mention that $final \: output$ is the resulting vector that is produced from forward propagation, $final \: output = \sigma(W^{T}x+b)$. The target variable $y$ should be a Bernoulli random vector consisting of $1$s and $0$s, it is normally labelled as $target$ in code implementation. And so to derive the second gradient we need to replace $\sigma(W^{T}x+b)$ with $final \: output$ and replace $y$ with the $target$ variable, then multiplicate the product with the hidden layers output, denoted $hidden \: output$. And as the result of this algebra is an array of gradients, we need to computate the sample average then chose it as the approximation of the second gradient, dw_2; the result,


$$\text{dW_2}=\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i}^{m} \big[ final \: output_{i} - target_{i} \big] \cdot hidden \: out_{i};$$


one can observe that $final \: output - target = error$ is the error formula, and that we are calculating the error between $final \: output$ (e.g. score) and $target$. We calculate the magnitude of the error to correct the difference between $final \: output$ (e.g. score) and $target$, we accomplish this by updating the weights and baises of the neural network with the aforementationed sampled average gradients. But we cannot simply apply this error measurement evenly across the hidden and outout layers, we instead need to adjust the error proportionally across hidden and output layers, so target update the weights and bias responsible for the error.
     If $n$ denotes the number of layers that makeup a neural network, then $(n-1)$ represents the number of layers that the error must be proportionally distributed over to correctly explain the errors origin. In our case with a feedforward neural network Logistic regression has three layers, so the error only needs to be distributed over two layers, the one output layer and the one hidden layer. Without further elaboration the first gradient is,


$$\text{dW_1} = \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i}^{m} \big( Who^{T} \cdot \big[ final \: output_{i} - target_{i} \big] - Who^{T} \cdot \big[ final \: output_{i} - target_{i} \big] \cdot \big( hidden \: output_{i} \big)^{2} \big) \cdot inputs_{i},$$


and subsequently, $Who^{T} \cdot \big[ final \: output_{i} - target_{i} \big]$ is the error from the output layer and $\big[ final \: output_{i} - target_{i} \big] \cdot \big( hidden \: output_{i} \big)^{2}$ is the error from the hidden layer; the difference measure is multplied with weight matrix, Who which proportions the error between the output and hidden layers based on the connection signal strengths.
     At last it should have become apparent that to implement a backward propagation phase with a manual differentiation schema is not a trivial task, and requires in-depth comprehension of the loss function, and know of how to derive the partial derivatives closed form solutions. For an automatic differentiation schema, only some comprehension of the loss function is required, and its implementation is more streamlined then a manual differentiation schema.
     In the following code block is the slightly modified source code to Micrograd.nn: its github can be located here [11]. Andrej Karpathy's heavy use of comprehensive lists made for compact code: the weights and baises are created through comprehensive list and are encapsulated with Micrograd.Value. The subsequent generated weights and baises are themselves captured through comprehensive list that makeup the weight matrix and bias vector specific to Layer(sz[i],sz[i+1],nonlin=i!=len(nouts)-1), where sz[i] it the prior layer and sz[i+1] is the posterior layer. Noting that even weight matrices and bais vectors are subsequently themselves captured inside another comprehensive list, which is parsed alongside $n-1$ storage elements, e.g., $n$ is the number of layers in the neural network.

class Module:
    def zero_grad(self):
        # Resets gradient derivative to zero
        for p in self.parameters():
            p.grad=0;
    def parameters(self):
        return [];
class Neuron(Module):
    def __init__(self,nin,nonlin=True):
        self.weights=[Value(np.random.uniform(-1,1)) for _ in range(nin)];
        self.bias=Value(0);
        self.nonlin=nonlin;
    def __call__(self,x):
        act=sum((wi*xi for wi,xi in zip(self.weights,x)),self.bias);
        return act.tanh() if self.nonlin else act;
    def parameters(self):
        return self.weights+[self.bias];
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"{'tanh()' if self.nonlin else 'Linear'}Neuron({len(self.weights)})";
    pass
class Layer(Module):
    def __init__(self,nin,nout,**kwargs):
        self.neurons=[Neuron(nin,**kwargs) for _ in range(nout)];
    def __call__(self,x):
        out=[n(x) for n in self.neurons];
        return out[0] if len(out) == 1 else out;
    def parameters(self):
        return [p for n in self.neurons for p in n.parameters()];
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Layer of [{', '.join(str(n) for n in self.neurons)}]";
class MLP(Module):
    def __init__(self,nin,nouts):
        sz=[nin]+nouts;
        self.layers=[Layer(sz[i],sz[i+1],nonlin=i!=len(nouts)-1) for i in range(len(nouts))];
    def __call__(self, x):
        for layer in self.layers:
            x=layer(x);
        return x;
    def parameters(self):
        return [p for layer in self.layers for p in layer.parameters()];
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"MLP of [{', '.join(str(layer) for layer in self.layers)}]";

There will not be a complete and exhaustive explanation for each of the pseudo-random sampling for each random vector, but there will be a selection of explanation of the most pertain sampling processes.
     Firstly used np.mean() and np.std() to attain the mean (e.g. $\mu_{tot \: balance}$) and standard deviation (e.g. $\sigma_{tot \: balance}$) of the original random vector, tot_balance. After, we used np.random.randn(len(tot_balance)) to return a standard normal random vector, $Z\mathcal{N}(\mu=0,\sigma^{2}=1)$ with length len(tot_balance), then used the following transformation,

$$X=\mu+\sigma*Z \to X = \mu_{tot \: balance} + \sigma_{tot \: balance} \cdot \mathcal{N}(\mu=0,\sigma^{2}=1) \to X = \mathcal{N}(\mu=\mu_{tot \: balance},\sigma^{2}=\sigma_{tot \: balance}^{2}),$$

this resulted in a normal random vector with almost the same statistical characteristics as the original random vector.

To note num_acc_30d_past_due_12_months is not a random variable but instead an indicator variable, which keeps track of a particular action or behavior. Hence as no pseudo-random sampling methodology exist in statistical simulation literature, we devised our own proprietary pseudo-random number sampler (PPRN) algorithm for this specific variable. The PPRN algorithm did not completely capture indicator variable's behavior, but it did achieve a very similar distribution characteristic; we decided this result was sufficient for this project purposes.

To feed the simulate credit card applicant dataset, df3, into the feedforward Neural Network (FFNN), the dataset was split between the feature variables denoted as X and the target variable denoted as Y. In addition as the FFNN cannot handle data in the pandas.core.frame.DataFrame format, the feature variables dataset X and target variable dataset Y had to be converted to numpy.ndarray format, which is a data format that the FFNN can handle, e.g. a data format that it can perform calcalutations upon, and thus use to train itself.

In [13]:
class Module:
    def zero_grad(self):
        # Resets gradient derivative to zero
        for p in self.parameters():
            p.grad=0;
    def parameters(self):
        return [];
class Neuron(Module):
    def __init__(self,nin,nonlin=True):
        self.weights=[Value(np.random.uniform(-1,1)) for _ in range(nin)];
        self.bias=Value(0);
        self.nonlin=nonlin;
    def __call__(self,x):
        act=sum((wi*xi for wi,xi in zip(self.weights, x)),self.bias);
        #return act;
        return act.tanh() if self.nonlin else act;
    def parameters(self):
        return self.weights+[self.bias];
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"{'tanh()' if self.nonlin else 'Linear'}Neuron({len(self.weights)})";
    pass
class Layer(Module):
    def __init__(self,nin,nout,**kwargs):
        self.neurons=[Neuron(nin,**kwargs) for _ in range(nout)];
    def __call__(self,x):
        out=[n(x) for n in self.neurons];
        return out[0] if len(out) == 1 else out;
    def parameters(self):
        return [p for n in self.neurons for p in n.parameters()];
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Layer of [{', '.join(str(n) for n in self.neurons)}]";
class MLP(Module):
    def __init__(self,nin,nouts):
        sz=[nin]+nouts;
        self.layers=[Layer(sz[i],sz[i+1],nonlin=i!=len(nouts)-1) for i in range(len(nouts))];
    def __call__(self, x):
        for layer in self.layers:
            x=layer(x);
        return x;
    def parameters(self):
        return [p for layer in self.layers for p in layer.parameters()];
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"MLP of [{', '.join(str(layer) for layer in self.layers)}]";

For different data types requires different loss functions, and in our case the target variable is a Bernoulli random vector, so the best loss function is the cross-entropy loss function, which is know in mathematics/statistics as the Bernoulli maximum likelihood estimate function (MLE). In the following code block contains the Python function named, loss; it the function that is responsible for the execution of forward propagation, calculation of the total loss and its L2-norm regularization, and the calculation of the current accuracy of the model. Upon execution loss returns a print to console statement contianing the models current total_loss and accuracy.

In [73]:
def loss(X,Y):
    # Forward propagation
    inputs = [list(map(Value, xrow)) for xrow in X]
    scores=list(map(model,inputs))
    scores=[((scorei)).sigmoid() for scorei in scores]
    
    # Bernoulli MLE loss function
    losses=[yi*(scorei.log())+(1-yi)*((1-scorei).log()) for yi,scorei in zip(Y,scores)];
    data_loss=sum(losses)*(1.0/len(losses));
    # L2-norm regularization
    alpha=(1/len(model.parameters()));
    reg_loss=alpha * sum((p*p.data for p in model.parameters()));
    total_loss=data_loss+reg_loss;
    
    # also get accuracy
    predictions=[scorei.data > 0.5 for scorei in scores];
    acc=[predi==yi.data for predi,yi in zip(predictions,Y)];
    accuracy=sum(acc)/len(acc);
    return total_loss,accuracy;

total_loss,acc=loss(X,Y);
print(total_loss,acc);

Have not defined the recursion, so the in the following code block, is the code to recursively executive the three phases of training: forward propagation, backward propagation and parameter updating. In [74]:
# optimization
for k in range(50):
    
    # forward propagation - returns total_loss and accuracy
    total_loss,acc=loss(X,Y);
    
    # backward propagation: reset gradients and generates new gradients
    model.zero_grad();
    total_loss.backward();
    
    # updates the parameters with Gradient Descent
    learning_rate=0.7
    for p in model.parameters():
        p.data-=learning_rate*p.grad;
    
    if k % 1 == 0:
        print(f"step {k} loss {total_loss.data}, accuracy {acc*100}%")

     The following code block contains the source-code to the neural network logistic regression classifier (NNLR) from [20]; one can observe the complexity to this implementation approach, though the advantage of this approach is its utilization of vectorized operations, which leverages how present-day CPU architecture computates; e.g., everything that is feed to a CPU is a data vector. Nevertheless this approach utilizes a computationally efficient methodology, which make it a quick algorithm to execute.

In [76]:
class Neural_Network:
    
    # Initiates the paremeters and activiation function 
    def __init__(self,inputnodes,hiddennodes,outputnodes,learningrate):
        # Set numbers of nodes in each layer
        self.inodes=inputnodes;
        self.hnodes=hiddennodes;
        self.onodes=outputnodes;
        
        # Generates two weight matrices of size (hnodes1 by inodes), (hnodes2 by hnodes1) and (onodes by hnodes2)
        # through a normal PRN of N(mu=0,sigma^2=inodes^-0.5), N(mu=0,sigma^2=hnodes1^-0.5), and N(mu=0,sigma^2=hnodes2^-0.5)
        #self.wih=np.random.normal(0.0,pow(self.inodes,-0.5),(self.hnodes,self.inodes));
        self.wih=np.random.randn(self.hnodes,self.inodes);
        self.b1=np.zeros((self.hnodes,1));
        #self.who=np.random.normal(0.0,pow(self.hnodes,-0.5),(self.onodes,self.hnodes));
        self.who=np.random.randn(self.onodes,self.hnodes);
        self.b2=np.zeros((self.onodes,1));

        
        #print("Wih = ");      # remove the print statement, as its generated output was multiple pages 
        #print(self.wih);
        #print(" ");
        #print("who = ");
        #print(self.who);
        
        # Learning rate of the Neural Network
        self.lr=learningrate;
        
        # Retrieves sigmoid activation function from scipy.special
        self.activation_function=lambda x: sp.expit(x);
        
        pass
    
    # Trians the Neural Network
    def forward_propagation(self,inputs):
        # Calculates the signals inputted in Hidden Layer 1 
        hidden_inputs=np.dot(self.wih,inputs)+self.b1;
        hidden_outputs=self.activation_function(hidden_inputs);
        
        # Calculates signal inputted in Output Layer
        final_inputs=np.dot(self.who,hidden_outputs)+self.b2;
        final_outputs=self.activation_function(final_inputs);
        
        self.hiddeninputs=hidden_inputs;  self.hiddenoutputs=hidden_outputs;
        self.finalinputs=final_inputs;    self.finaloutputs=final_outputs;
        
        pass
    
    def forward_propagation2(self,X,parameters):
        W1=parameters["W1"];
        b1=parameters["b1"];
        W2=parameters["W2"];
        b2=parameters["b2"];
    
        # Implement Forward Propagation to calculate A2 (probabilities)
        Z1=np.dot(W1,X)+b1;
        A1=self.activation_function(Z1);
        Z2=np.dot(W2,A1)+b2;
        A2=self.activation_function(Z2);
    
        assert(A2.shape==(1,X.shape[1]));
    
        # Values needed in the backpropagation are stored in "cache". 
        # This will be given as an input to the backpropagation
        cache = {"Z1": Z1,
                 "A1": A1,
                 "Z2": Z2,
                 "A2": A2}
    
        return A2, cache;
    
    def backward_propagation(self,inputs,targets):
        m=inputs.shape[1];
        
        dZ_2=self.finaloutputs-targets;
        dW_2=(1/m)*np.dot(dZ_2,self.hiddenoutputs.T);
        db_2=(1/m)*(np.sum(dZ_2,axis=1,keepdims=True));
        dZ_1=np.dot(self.who.T,dZ_2)*(1-self.hiddenoutputs**2);
        dW_1=(1/m)*(np.dot(dZ_1,inputs.T));
        db_1=(1/m)*(np.sum(dZ_1,axis=1,keepdims=True));
        
        self.dW1=dW_1; self.db1=db_1; self.dW2=dW_2; self.db2=db_2;
        
        pass
    
    def compute_cost(self,Y):
        m=Y.shape[0];
        
        logprobs=np.multiply(Y,np.log(self.finaloutputs))+np.multiply((1-Y),np.log(1-self.finaloutputs));
        cost=(-1/m)*np.sum(logprobs);
        
        cost=float(np.squeeze(cost));
        
        assert(isinstance(cost,float));
        
        return cost;
    
    def update_parameters(self):
        self.wih=self.wih-self.lr*self.dW1;
        self.b1=self.b1-self.lr*self.db1;
        self.who=self.who-self.lr*self.dW2;
        self.b2=self.b2-self.lr*self.db2;
    
        pass
    
    def predict(self,x,parameters):
        A2,cache=n.forward_propagation2(x,parameters);
        predictions=(A2 > 0.5)
        
        return predictions;

    def train(self,inputs,targets,MaxIter=10000,print_cost=True):
        
        for i in range(0,MaxIter):
            n.forward_propagation(inputs);
            cost=n.compute_cost(targets);
            n.backward_propagation(inputs,targets);
            n.update_parameters();
            if print_cost and i % 1000 == 0:
                print("Cost after iteration %i: %f"%(i,cost));
        
        parameters={"W1": self.wih,
                  "b1": self.b1,
                  "W2": self.who,
                  "b2": self.b2}       
        
        return parameters;

     A common problem in mathematics is the interpolation of functions and data with interpolation methods; the most conventional method that have been utilizes range from legendre polynomials to hermite polynomials to spline interpolation. But during the 1990s mathematicians venture of the concept of utilizing neural networks as universal approximators [22, 23], some sampling of literature, Constructive approximate interpolation by neural networks (2006) by B. Llanas and F.J. Sainz [24], A rapid supervised learning neural network for function interpolation and approximation (1996) by C.L.P. Chen [25], and Artificial neural networks as a tool for spatial interpolation by Juan P. Rigol, Claire H. Jarvis and Neil Stuart [26].
     In case of the NNLR model, because it possesses a hardcoded code architecture for it to become an interpolating neural network; we would have to rewrite entire Neural_Network class function. In the case of the four-layered neural network generated by Micrograd, the only portion of the code was must change is the loss function; then it would become capable of interpolating a mathematics function, such as, $f(x)=x^{2}$. Consequentially we computated $f(x)=x^{2}$ and plotted the result in the following code block.

# loss function
def loss(X,Y):
    Xb=X; y=Y;
    inputs=[[Value(xrow)] for xrow in Xb];
    
    # feed-forward the model to get scores (e.g. model's predictions)
    scores=list(map(model,inputs));
    
    # Mean Squared Error loss function
    losses=[(yi-scorei)**2 for yi, scorei in zip(y,scores)];
    total_loss=sum(losses)*(1.0/len(losses));
    
    # L2-Norm error formula
    diff=[yi-scorei.data for yi,scorei in zip(Y,scores)] 
    L2_Norm=np.linalg.norm(diff);
    return total_loss,L2_Norm;

total_loss,L2Norm=loss(X,Y);

# loss function
def loss(X,Y):
    Xb=X; y=Y;
    inputs=[[Value(xrow)] for xrow in Xb];
    
    # Forward propagation: feed-forward the model to get scores (e.g. model's predictions)

    losses=[np.linalg.norm(yi-scorei) for yi,scorei in zip(y,scores)];

    # also get accuracy
    diff=[yi-scorei.data for yi,scorei in zip(Y,scores)]

In conclusion Micrograd is a fantastic Python package for neural network development, it usage can be from proto-typing neural network concepts to low intensity real-world data applications. The significant issue that hold this package back is the lack of parallelization, though that was not part of Andrej Karpathy's original intent for this Python package. And anyhow, if one model require million by million dataset, PyTorch is the more appropriate for medium and high intensity application, as it possesses parallelization functionality. Nevertheless Micrograd is a great teaching tool for neural network development, and a fantastic tool for low-intensity neural network appliations, such as credit card applicant selection and univariate function approximation.
     This will conlude our inquiry on this topic; in the next project, we will cover the use of Pytorch and parallelization. We hope this project was useful for the reader, and we wish the reader a wonderful day.
